      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing leaves on the lower stems of your tomato plants are a common issue, often caused by a lack of light or a root bound condition. It's as if the lower leaves are being \"sucked dry\" by the plant's energy, leaving them to wither and turn yellow. You can try pruning the lower leaves to improve air circulation and reduce moisture, which can help prevent fungal diseases that thrive in damp conditions. \n\nAs for the soil, it's possible that the lower stems are experiencing a \"gobbling\" of nutrients, leaving the top leaves to continue growing. To fix this, you can try adding a balanced fertilizer to the soil, making sure to water it in thoroughly. However, if the soil is too dense, it's a good idea to \"dig in\" some organic matter like compost or well-rotted manure to improve drainage and aeration. \n\nKeep in mind that tomato plants can be quite sensitive to soil pH, so it's essential to check the pH level and adjust it if necessary. A slightly acidic to neutral pH (around 6.0-7.0) is ideal for most tomato varieties. If the soil is too alkaline, it can cause nutrient deficiencies, leading to yellow",
      "source": "target",
